{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01KAz4gVYVRMrfcR9VqiTz42","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to generate 10 realistic fake OCR recipe text files. Let me break down the requirements:\n\n1. Save to `tools/title-loop/input/{RECIPE_TITLE}.generated.18.txt`\n2. Filename rules:\n   - Use SPACES (not hyphens or underscores)\n   - Preserve Polish diacritics\n   - Filename title must EXACTLY match the main title in text content (case-insensitive OK)\n\n3. Recipe mix: ~60% English, ~40% Polish\n4. Variety of categories\n5. Mix of single and multi-word titles\n\n6. AVOID these existing recipes (there's a long list)\n\n7. Pattern requirements:\n   - 5 files with SPLIT_TITLE (title split across 2-4 lines)\n   - 3 files with METADATA_PREFIX (category/serving info before title)\n   - 2 files with OCR_CORRUPTION (misrecognized characters)\n\n8. File length: 15-60 lines (spillover files 40-60)\n\nLet me plan my 10 recipes (need to ensure they're different from the existing ones):\n\n**Polish recipes (need 4 for the 40% portion, let me aim for about 4-5 Polish):**\n1. Żabka (Frog legs) - SPLIT_TITLE\n2. Krupnik (Polish barley soup) - METADATA_PREFIX\n3. Flaki (Beef tripe) - OCR_CORRUPTION\n4. Zrazy Mięsne (Beef rolls) - regular\n5. Bigos Myśliwski - SPLIT_TITLE\n\n**English recipes (need 5-6 for the 60% portion):**\n1. Risotto al Tartufo - SPLIT_TITLE\n2. Beef Wellington - METADATA_PREFIX\n3. Crème Brûlée - OCR_CORRUPTION\n\n\n4. Shakshuka - METADATA_PREFIX\n5. Thai Green Curry - regular\n6. Paella Valenciana - SPLIT_TITLE\n\nNow I need to finalize my selection. I have 5 SPLIT_TITLE, 3 METADATA_PREFIX, and 2 OCR_CORRUPTION accounted for, which gives me exactly 10 files. The Polish-to-English ratio works out to roughly 4 Polish and 6 English recipes, matching the 40/60 split. I need to verify the count: 5 + 3 + 2 = 10 total. That accounts for all the dishes. The final allocation is set with five files marked as SPLIT_TITLE (Żabka, Risotto al Tartufo, Paella Valenciana, Thai Green Curry, Zurek Myśliwski), three as METADATA_PREFIX (Krupnik, Beef Wellington, Shakshuka), and two as OCR_CORRUPTION (Flaki, Crème Brûlée).\n\nHowever, checking against the exclusion list reveals a problem—\"Flaki do potraw\" is already listed, so I need to replace Flaki with another Polish dish that fits the OCR_CORRUPTION category. \"Kaczka z Jabłkami\" would work as a suitable alternative.\n\nAfter verifying the updated list against the exclusion criteria, all ten recipes are clear. Now I'm generating the OCR text files themselves, applying the three corruption types: splitting titles across lines for SPLIT_TITLE entries, adding metadata prefixes like serving information before titles for METADATA_PREFIX entries, and introducing character recognition errors for OCR_CORRUPTION entries. For the single-word Polish dish \"Żabka,\" I need to consider how to meaningfully split it across lines while maintaining the spirit of the corruption pattern shown in the examples.\n\nLooking at the examples more carefully, SPLIT_TITLE works better with multi-word titles that can be naturally divided. I'm reconsidering my selections to use dishes with compound names that split more effectively—like \"Żabka z Masłem\" instead of just \"Żabka,\" and \"Żurek Myśliwski\" instead of \"Zurek Myśliwski.\" This gives me better material to work with for creating realistic line breaks in the OCR output.\n\nI should also verify against the exclusion list to ensure I'm not duplicating existing recipes. While \"Żurek\" appears in the list, \"Żurek Myśliwski\" is a distinct variant. Similarly, \"Kaczka Pieczona\" is excluded, but \"Kaczka z Wiśniami\" is different enough. To be safer, I'm swapping some entries—replacing \"Kaczka z Wiśniami\" with \"Gęsina z Jabłkami\" and \"Żurek Myśliwski\" with \"Zrazy Mięsne ze Śmietaną\"—to ensure better diversity and avoid any potential overlap with the existing dataset.\n\nNow I'm checking my revised list of ten recipes against the exclusion criteria. Each one—from \"Żabka z Masłem\" through \"Thai Green Curry\"—passes verification. I'm ready to generate the actual file content, starting with realistic OCR text that captures ingredients and preparation steps with varying quality levels to simulate authentic document degradation.\n\nFor the first file, I'm creating \"Żabka z Masłem\" with a split title format showing the Polish frog dish. The OCR includes ingredient measurements, step-by-step cooking instructions from rinsing and flouring the frogs through the final simmering in broth with herbs, plus timing details and serving size. The second file begins \"Krupnik Litewski\" formatted as metadata with seasonal tags and time estimates, introducing a traditional Lithuanian soup with the OCR text starting to describe its preparation. Gęsina z jabłkami to danie, w którym drób piecze się z owocami. Potrzebuję całą gęsinę o wadze około 2,5 kg, kilogram zielonych jabłek, mąkę, cebulę, sól, pieprz, tymianek i majeranek, plus białe wino. Gęsinę oczyszczam i wysuszam, jabłka kroję na połowy bez pestek, a następnie pieczę w piekarniku w temperaturze 180°C, polewając co 15 minut.\n\nDrób powinien być złoty i chrupiący, a jabłka dodaję 30 minut przed końcem pieczenia. Po wyjęciu z piekarnika czekam 10 minut w temperaturze pokojowej, zanim podaję na gorąco. Całe pieczenie zajmuje około 2 godzin i wystarczy na 6-8 porcji.\n\nDrugie danie to zrazy mięsne ze śmietaną — tradycyjne mięso wołowe nadziewane. Używam 800 gramów mielonego mięsa wołowego, słoninę, jajka, cebulę, pietruszką, bułkę żytnią, śmietanę, marchewkę, sól i pieprz. Bułkę namaczam w mleku jako pierwszy krok przygotowania. pot. Sauté the shallot in butter until softened, then add the rice and stir to coat each grain. Deglaze with white wine and begin adding the hot broth one ladle at a time, stirring constantly and waiting for each addition to be absorbed before adding more. After about 18 minutes, the rice becomes creamy and al dente. Finish by stirring in the Parmesan and truffle oil off the heat, taste to adjust seasoning, and serve right away with fresh truffle shavings if desired. The whole process takes roughly 10 minutes to prep and 20 minutes to cook, serving four people.\n\n---\n\nA beef tenderloin is seared on all sides until golden, then cooled before being layered with pâté and a mushroom duxelles made from finely chopped mushrooms cooked with shallots. The prepared beef is wrapped in prosciutto, then encased entirely in puff pastry and brushed with egg wash. It bakes at 200°C for 35-40 minutes until the pastry turns golden, followed by a 10-minute rest before slicing.\n\nThe recipe yields 6-8 servings. For the crème brûlée, heavy cream is heated with a vanilla pod until it simmers, then whisked egg yolks combined with caster sugar are slowly tempered with the hot cream mixture.\n\nThe custard is strained through a fine sieve, poured into ramekins, and baked in a water bath at 160°C for 15-18 minutes until set. After chilling for 4 hours, the dessert is finished by torching caramelized sugar on top and served immediately while still hot. Total preparation involves about 18 minutes of active cooking time.\n\nFor the shakshuka recipe, eggs are baked in a spiced tomato sauce. The dish requires 20 minutes to cook and serves 4 people. Key ingredients include 6 eggs, fresh tomatoes, onion, peppers, garlic, paprika, cumin, cayenne pepper, olive oil, and fresh cilantro. The preparation begins by heating olive oil in a large pan and sautéing the onion and garlic with peppers for about 5 minutes, then adding tomatoes and spices to simmer for 10 minutes. Eggs are cracked directly into the sauce, covered, and cooked for another 5 minutes until the whites set while yolks remain soft. The dish is served with bread or pita.\n\nFor the paella, I'm heating the broth with saffron to infuse flavor, then sautéing aromatics and rice in olive oil before gradually adding the hot liquid. The key is avoiding stirring—letting the rice cook undisturbed allows it to develop properly. Beans and tomatoes go in after 15 minutes, and the whole dish finishes when the rice absorbs the liquid and a golden crust forms on the bottom, which is the desirable socarrat.\n\nFor the Thai curry, I'm starting by heating oil in a wok to build the base for the curry paste and aromatics.\n\nThe paste gets fried briefly to release its fragrance, then coconut cream is stirred in to create a rich foundation. Chicken goes in next for a quick sear before the coconut milk is added to bring everything together into a simmering sauce. Eggplant and bamboo shoots cook until tender in about 10 minutes, then fish sauce, lime juice, and palm sugar balance the flavors. Fresh Thai basil is added at the end to preserve its delicate taste, and the whole dish comes together in roughly 30 minutes total, serving four people.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":12699,"cache_read_input_tokens":65286,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":12699},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9aab07eb-21b8-49fe-9f06-0a0b66a4125f","uuid":"d806a648-a82f-4bf7-95a6-8c24d74f5f66"}
